body: I actually started off optimising constant builtin method calls here and ended up doing a lot of additional optimisations for f-strings. Especially the expression deduplication seems a very neat improvement, although there's a tiny risk of diverting from strict Python semantics. It's difficult to run into for users, though.

commit.message: Evaluate constant f-strings and (safe) method calls on literals during constant folding.
Be more relaxed about what we consider a builtin method.
Exclude some not-so-safe builtin methods that were added or modified after Py3.7 (the oldest Python that we currently support).

Clean up "inferred_method_return_types" and "safe_compile_time_methods" dicts to bring them in alphabetical order.
Update them from Py3.13.
Add a helper function "is_safe_compile_time_method()" to avoid using the "safe_compile_time_methods dict directly outside of the module.

Negate the "safe_compile_time_methods" table to make it more maintainable.
We now use the "inferred_method_return_types" table as basis and only exclude the unsafe methods from that. This automatically ignores modifiers (that return None) and future new builtin methods that are yet unknown.
Add a test to validate both tables.

milestone.description:
* Remove code for Python 2 and Python < 3.7.
* Integrate better with Python 3.
* Improve support for the Limited API.
* Start supporting GIL-free Python 3.13.
* Support the Py3.13 `sys.monitoring` API.
* Support and use `am_send` for coroutines.

title: Optimise constant f-strings and constant builtin method calls
